{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488815","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488815"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:58:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:58:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"550"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"550","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/550"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.4,0.49,0.03,0.07,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"550"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43589"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"550","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/550"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"550"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28605"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"457"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5061"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6105"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43800"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43589"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man presents with a three-week history of right upper quadrant pain and lethargy. He reports no history of weight loss and no past episodes of similar pain. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He has a 40 pack-year smoking history and drinks 60 gm alcohol a day. He works as a sheep farmer. On physical examination his pulse rate is 85/min, blood pressure 135/90 mmHg, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. There is some tenderness in the right upper quadrant. A CT scan of the abdomen is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hydatid cyst of the liver","Liver abscess","Acute cholecystitis","Hepatocellular carcinoma","Metastatic liver disease"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis is \u003Cstrong\u003Eliver abscess\u003C/strong\u003E. This is a typical radiology finding of liver abscess, characterised with a homogeneous single or multilocular cavity with air-fluid interface. This patient has a large intrahepatic abscess with a gas-fluid interface indicating the presence of gas-forming organism. Patients with liver abscess present with right upper quadrant pain accompanied by infectious symptoms of fever and malaise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute cholecystitis\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely as the CT scan result shows no abnormality within the gallbladder region. CT scans of patients with acute cholecystitis usually demonstrate thickening of the gallbladder wall with some distension and pericholecystic fluid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatocellular carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E clinically presents with jaundice, ascites, and constitutional symptoms of anorexia and weight loss. On CT imaging, hepatocellular carcinoma lesions is characteristically more hypervascular and solid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydatid cyst of the liver \u003C/strong\u003Ehave a characteristic calcified rim - which is not demonstrated in this case. Hydatid cyst can also present with daughter cysts on CT imaging. It is uncommon for hydatid cyst to present with air-fluid interface.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetastatic liver disease \u003C/strong\u003Epresent as multiple lobulated solid lesions with possible central necrosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Patients with liver abscess present with right upper quadrant pain accompanied by infectious symptoms of fever and malaise."],"references":["Gomez I Gavara C, L\u00f3pez-And\u00fajar R, Belda Ib\u00e1\u00f1ez T, Ramia \u00c1ngel JM, Moya Herraiz \u00c1, Orbis Castellanos F, et al. Review of the treatment of liver hydatid cysts. World J Gastroenterol 2015;21:124-31. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4284328/","Choi JY, Lee JM, Sirlin CB. CT and MR imaging diagnosis and staging of hepatocellular carcinoma: part I. Development, growth, and spread: key pathologic and imaging aspects. Radiology. 2014;272(3):635-54. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25153274/","Namasivayam S, Martin DR, Saini S. Imaging of liver metastases: MRI. Cancer Imaging. 2007;7(1):2. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17293303/","Alsaif HS, Venkatesh SK, Chan DS, Archuleta S. CT appearance of pyogenic liver abscesses caused by Klebsiella pneumoniae. Radiology. 2011;260(1):129-38. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21460028/","Shakespear JS, Shaaban AM, Rezvani M. CT findings of acute cholecystitis and its complications. AJR Am J Roentgenol. 2010;194(6):1523-9. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20489092/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28605"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"550"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14338"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14338","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14338"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/eaa844de-e9bb-491b-91df-685bbf2b7f56.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/eaa844de-e9bb-491b-91df-685bbf2b7f56.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":684,"height":600}},{"type":"itemR